      <h1>Dunearn House Review: The First Swiss Club Enclave Condo in 33 Years &mdash; Worth the Hype?</h1>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article class="post-content">
    <img src="/assets/images/dunearn-house-cover.jpg" alt="Dunearn House — Frasers Property × CSC Land × Sekisui House's CCR launch in the Swiss Club enclave, the first GLS plot in the Bukit Timah Turf City master plan" loading="eager" decoding="async" />

    <p style="font-style:italic; color:var(--muted);">A ~6 minute read for buyers weighing up the most contested CCR launch of the cycle &mdash; before the showflat marketing takes over.</p>

    <div style="background:var(--paper); border-left:4px solid var(--copper); padding:24px 28px; border-radius:0 var(--radius) var(--radius) 0; margin:1.5em 0 2em;">
      <strong style="color:var(--teal); display:block; margin-bottom:8px;">TL;DR</strong>
      <p style="margin-bottom:0;"><strong>Dunearn House</strong> is the Frasers Property &times; CSC Land Group &times; Sekisui House launch in the Swiss Club enclave of District 11 &mdash; the <strong>first non-landed residential development in this subzone for 33 years</strong>, and the <strong>first GLS plot</strong> in the massive Bukit Timah Turf City rejuvenation master plan. ~370 units, fresh 99-year lease (~98 remaining), a sub-5-minute walk (~476&nbsp;m) to <strong>Sixth Avenue MRT (DTL)</strong>, and inside the 1&nbsp;km <strong>MGS Primary</strong> catchment. On the NAVIS PrimeKey Analysis it scores <strong>35 / 40 (87.5%) &mdash; 4.4 out of 5 stars</strong>: five-star marks on connectivity, growth hotspot, yield, tenure and project size. The lone weak spot: zero HDB MOP supply within 10 years, which cuts short-term upgrader demand but ring-fences the enclave&rsquo;s exclusivity. Verdict: <strong>Strong Buy for income investors, school-driven families and long-horizon CCR buyers</strong>. Less suited to short-term flippers waiting on a wave of HDB upgraders. Preview window <strong>10&ndash;21 July 2026</strong> &middot; Sale launch day <strong>25 July 2026</strong>.</p>
    </div>

    <p>It&rsquo;s been more than three decades since a new non-landed development opened in the Swiss Club subzone. That single line is doing most of the marketing work for <strong>Dunearn House</strong>, and not without reason &mdash; in Singapore property, supply-constrained micro-markets are where capital preservation actually happens.</p>

    <p>But scarcity alone isn&rsquo;t a thesis. Dunearn House sits at a genuinely interesting intersection: a CCR enclave that no developer has touched in a generation, the first GLS plot of the Bukit Timah Turf City master plan, and an unusually rare pairing of <em>elite school catchment</em> with <em>sub-5-minute MRT walk</em>. Nine developers bid for this site &mdash; that tells you more about the underlying fundamentals than any rendering ever will.</p>

    <p>Below we walk through the five angles you&rsquo;ll hear from every agent, then run Dunearn House through the <a href="/blog/primekey-analysis-introduction">NAVIS PrimeKey Analysis</a> &mdash; the 8-pillar framework we use to grade any Singapore project on data, not on hype.</p>

