    <h2>Who is Dunearn House actually for?</h2>

    <p>Strip away the launch noise and the buyer profile is unusually clean:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Income-focused CCR investors</strong> &mdash; a 3%+ projected gross yield in District 11 is rare. School + MRT + scarcity stack the demand drivers.</li>
      <li><strong>Families with school priorities</strong> &mdash; a 1&nbsp;km MGS Primary catchment in a low-density Swiss Club setting, with Nanyang/Hwa Chong/NJC in the neighbourhood.</li>
      <li><strong>Long-horizon CCR capital-growth buyers</strong> &mdash; positioning ahead of the Turf City catalyst chain rather than chasing this quarter&rsquo;s rebound.</li>
      <li><strong>Owner-occupiers who value silhouette and silence</strong> &mdash; elevated above the surrounding GCB estates, sweeping vistas, boutique scale.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>It&rsquo;s a weaker fit if your underwriting depends on a wave of nearby HDB upgraders driving a 3&ndash;5 year resale flip. That demand pool isn&rsquo;t in this micro-market, and won&rsquo;t be inside the modelling window. For long holders, that&rsquo;s the feature, not the bug.</p>

    <p>As always, the responsible next step is to <em>see the data before you see the showflat</em>. Read the PrimeKey Report above, line it up against any other CCR shortlist you&rsquo;re considering, and decide on facts &mdash; not on the brochure&rsquo;s rendering quality.</p>

